e next poll cycle. For the insufficient balance test, I can't rely on the `createMatch` page object since it waits for success—instead I'll manually trigger the creation and assert on the error toast that appears when it fails.\n\nWriting test setup... Writing test cases...\n\nI'm realizing the key issue here: after A claims and the match PDA closes, B's context might not automatically refresh to reflect that the match is no longer available. So when B tries to click the settle button, the question is whether B gets an error because the match is gone, or if B's stale context still shows the button as clickable. I need to verify whether the context has polling that would detect the match closure, or if B would be working with outdated state. stable after showing the result. B's \"Settle & Return\" button stays visible until B clicks it. Since A and B are in completely separate browser contexts with independent storage and sessions, A's claim transaction won't affect B's JavaScript state—only what B sees if it polls the blockchain. So when B clicks \"Settle & Return\" after A has already claimed and closed the match PDA, the transaction will fail during simulation against the now-closed account, triggering an error toast.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the test code. I need to be careful with the `claimOrSettle()` helper though—it might wait for a \"Back to Lobby\" confirmation that won't appear if there's an error, so I should manually click the button for B's settle action instead and handle the error response directly. aimOrSettle(page) — Click claim/settle button in sidebar, wait for \"Back to Lobby\". If the transaction fails, \"Back to Lobby\" won't appear and an error toast shows instead, so this would timeout on a failed claim. I should click the button and assert an error toast appears instead.\n\nThe error text depends on what happens when the match PDA is closed — it could be \"Simulation failed,\" \"account not found,\" or \"This match is no longer available\" 