on is what happens when B clicks join on that stale card — the join logic either pre-fetches the match account on-chain and errors immediately if it's closed, or it skips the pre-fetch and attempts to build the transaction directly.\n\nEither way, an error should surface when the PDA doesn't exist. I'm going to write the test code now with flexible error assertions to handle whatever the implementation does.\n\nOne more thing about test 2: both A and B get fresh browser contexts, so A creates a match and sees the active view, B navigates separately and sees the match in the lobby, then when A cancels, A's page returns to the lobby while B's page still shows the stale card for another 30 seconds.\n\nFor test 3, I need the full lifecycle: A creates, B joins, they wait for VRF resolution with A winning, A claims, then B tries to settle and gets an error. I also need to set up beforeAll to initialize the localnet and fund both players with their starting balances.\n\nWriting the test code... I need to create a Connection manually in the beforeAll hook since fixtures aren't available there, similar to how fundTestWallets() handles it internally.\n\nNow I'm setting up the beforeAll block to initialize the localnet and fund both test wallets with different amounts — Player A gets a minimal balance to test insufficient funds, while Player B gets a normal amount.\n\nI'm checking whether `test.describe.serial()` is actually supported in Playwright to ensure tests run sequentially with a shared worker, though I'm realizing that even with serial execution, each test still gets its own fixture instances.\n\nThe key insight is that while browser contexts refresh per test, the underlying blockchain state persists across the local validator, so a single Connection can work throughout all tests in the suite.\n\nSetting up the test file structure... await initializeLocalnet();\n    const connection = new Connection(LOCAL_RPC_URL, \"confirmed\");\n    // Fund Player A with minimal SOL