age. Player A's console should be clean, while B's console may log the failed transaction as part of the expected error flow.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the Playwright API for running tests serially — I need to verify whether `test.describe.serial` is the right approach or if I should use `test.describe.configure({ mode: 'serial' })` instead, and I should check what version of Playwright the project is using to ensure compatibility.\n\nLet me just go with `test.describe.serial` for now and address any compatibility issues if they come up. I'm also double-checking the error toast assertions — the \"Insufficient balance\" message should match what `parseTransactionError` returns, and for the cancelled match scenario, I need to consider whether the error comes from a pre-fetch check or a transaction simulation failure.\n\nEither way, a toast should appear, so I'll just assert visibility without checking specific text for those cases.\n\nBut there's a possibility the context handles a null fetch gracefully by removing the stale match from the list instead of showing an error toast. If that's what the code does, then my test expecting an error message would fail. Since I can't easily run the E2E tests right now to verify the actual behavior, I need to decide whether to test against the spec or the implementation—and testing what the code actually does makes more sense.\n\nI'm going to assume the most likely scenario: the context's `joinMatch` will attempt to build and send a transaction, it'll fail, and the error gets caught and displayed as a toast. That's the natural flow without special null-handling logic. I'll write the test based on that assumption and add a comment explaining the expected behavior. I should also be careful about console error tracking for player B, since the error flow will naturally produce console errors—I won't assert that B's console stays clean.\n\nLet me check the `trackConsoleErrors` implementation...\n\nExamining the error tracking utility...\n\nThe filter already excludes favicon, font, and cookie errors, but transaction failures from Solana would still show up as console errors. Since those are expected in error flow tests, I shouldn't call `assertClean()` on player B's console.\n\nFor test 1 with just player A, the Solana RPC error gets caught in the context's try/catch block and sets error state without logging to console, so `consoleA.assertClean()` should pass.\n\nHowever, the wallet adapter or web3.js library might log errors independently, so I'll take a safer approach: skip console assertions for the player experiencing the error, but assert clean console for any other players. This means for test 1 I'll skip A's assertion entirely since A is the only player, for test 2 I'll assert A's console is clean since B experiences the error, and for test 3 I'll do the same. I'm settling on a practical approach: track console errors throughout for debugging, but only assert that the console is clean for players who don't encounter transaction errors, while skipping assertions for whoever triggers the error to avoid false failures from expected wallet adapter logs.\n\nActually, the simplest path is to just skip console tracking entirely for these error-flow tests since the focus is on verifying error toasts appear. I'm checking the `assertErrorToast` helper to confirm it waits for visibility before checking the message text, which it does with a configurable timeout.\n\nFor tests where I don't know the exact error message, I'll just check that the toast is visible without asserting on specific text. The key timing concern is whether the async error handling completes fast enough—when the create button is clicked, it triggers the transaction flow, which fails and shows the toast. With a 10-second timeout in the assertion, that should be plenty of time, and since toasts don't auto-dismiss, they'll stay visible for the test to catch them.\n\nNow I'm deciding on the right Playwright API for running tests serially. The older `test.describe.serial` syntax is simpler but deprecated in newer versions, so I should use the `test.describe.configure({ mode: 'serial' })` approach instead to ensure compatibility.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6224,"cache_read_input_tokens":80058,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6224},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9011bcd3-c1e3-4ba2-996b-dc56e2b15fd6","uuid":"66784398-533a-478f-b3ad-45e951c63d17"}
