tent":"import { defineConfig, devices } from \"@playwright/test\";\n\n/**\n * Playwright config for local E2E integration tests.\n *\n * Runs against a local solana-test-validator with real wallet mode.\n * The validator + program deploy is handled by external bootstrap scripts;\n * this config only starts the Vite dev server.\n */\nexport default defineConfig({\n  testDir: \"./e2e\",\n  fullyParallel: false,\n  forbidOnly: !!process.env.CI,\n  retries: 0,\n  workers: 1,\n  reporter: \"list\",\n  timeout: 60_000,\n\n  use: {\n    baseURL: \"http://localhost:3002\",\n    screenshot: \"off\",\n    trace: \"retain-on-failure\",\n    ...devices[\"Desktop Chrome\"],\n    viewport: { width: 1280, height: 1080 },\n  },\n\n  projects: [\n    {\n      name: \"local-e2e\",\n      testMatch: \"local/**/*.spec.ts\",\n      use: { ...devices[\"Desktop Chrome\"], viewport: { width: 1280, height: 1080 } },\n    },\n  ],\n\n  webServer: {\n    command: \"npx vite --port 3002\",\n    url: \"http://localhost:3002\",\n    reuseExistingServer: !process.env.CI,\n    timeout: 30_000,\n    env: {\n      VITE_MOCK_MODE: \"false\",\n      VITE_TEST_WALLET: \"true\",\n      VITE_RPC_URL: \"http://127.0.0.1:8899\",\n      VITE_SOLANA_NETWORK: \"localnet\",\n    },\n  },\n});\n","numLines":48,"startLine":1,"totalLines":48}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MDh684PL4y4rvhc1urKict","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. `workers: 1` and `fullyParallel: false` — tests run serially with one worker. This means spec files run one after another. Since the worker is 1, all tests share the same validator state sequentially.\n\nWith `workers: 1`, I don't strictly need `test.describe.serial` because all tests already run serially. But it's good for documentation/clarity that the tests within this describe block are sequential and depend on each other.\n\nActually, since `fullyParallel: false` and `workers: 1`, all tests in all files run serially. So I don't even need `describe.serial`. \n\nI could use `test.describe.configure({ mode: 'serial' })` for clarity, but I'm realizing the real benefit is that serial mode skips remaining tests in a group if one fails — which matters here since my tests form a dependency chain where later tests rely on earlier state being valid.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: test 2 and test 3 are fairly independent since test 2 just funds more SOL and test 3 starts fresh. The `workers: 1` config already ensures sequential execution, so serial mode is more about preventing cascading failures than actual necessity. But that's still valuable for cleaner output.\n\nI'm going to go with `test.describe.configure({ mode: 'serial' })` to skip dependent tests if one fails, then write out the final test file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":759,"cache_read_input_tokens":105382,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":759},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9011bcd3-c1e3-4ba2-996b-dc56e2b15fd6","uuid":"993949ee-c906-45ab-9e9b-814988c2fff4"}
